{"id":14881505,"mediaExerciseId":"cbc58594-4b27-49f9-b7e0-b87684238d12","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"15","chapterTitle":"Raising Capital","groupId":612403,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":529,"solutions":[{"id":6019708,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we assess the bond ratings and flotation costs. \n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **non-investment grade bond** is a high-yield bond with a risky financial grade relative to the issuer's potential defaulting. The probability of the firm repaying its outstanding debt is regarded as uncertain in this investment grade. \n\nSince non-investment grade bonds are uncertain, they are riskier and more difficult to sell from the standpoint of an investment firm. Firms that invest in non-investment bondsÂ should be willing to take on many risks.\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Credit rating agencies give **investment-grade issuers** better ratings because they are thought to have a reduced risk of default. These bonds have lower returns and are considered better and more dependable securities.\n\nIf all other factors are equal, a bond with a better rating will have a lower interest rate. This type of investment is related to publicly listed firms and government agencies with a positive perspective.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"bfe880e4-5a51-4e44-9798-8db06a2ce315","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"h